{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580357/1949061601/0473.xml":{"full_text":"Thursday, June 16, 1949\nyear.\nAMA Gives Ground But\nBucks Health\nAtlantic City (LPA)\u2014Determin-\u25a0\ned to fight to the bitter end against\na program of compulsory health in\nsurance, the American Medical\nAss\u2019n at its annual sessions here\ngave ground on many other fronts\nwhere unions and consumer organ\nisations have been urging the\ndoctors to catch up with the times.\nThe medicos heard a pep-talk by\nClem Whitaker, of the public re\nlations firm of Whitaker Baxter,\nwhich is spending the $2,500,000\n\u201ceducation\u201d fund that the AMA\nhas assessed its members to fight\nhealth insurance. He reported that,\nbesides the $100,000 his firm will\nreceive for salary and travel ex\npenses, most of the $900,000 to be\nspent this year will go for litera\nture. He figures it will take\nthrough 1951 to \u201click this damn\nthing.\u201d\nAs for giving ground, the AMA\u2019s\nHouse of Delegates took these\nactions: 1\u2014Approved a set of 20\nstandards under which union and\nconsumer-sponsored health plans\ncould be approved by local medical\nsocieties. AFL and CIO experts\nhad worked through the Coopera\ntive Health Federation in nego\ntiations with AMA that resulted in\nthe 20 points. Chairman Dean\nClark of CHFA said the action\n\u201cmay constitute no more than lip\nservice ijnless a marked change\ntakes place in the attitude of cer\ntain of the state and local medical\nsocieties toward efforts of the peo\nple to solve voluntarily for them\nselves their economic problems\nconnected with medical care.\u201d\n2\u2014Called for late summer or fall\na conference of doctors and hospi\ntal administrators as well as labor,\nconsumer and government spokes\nmen to discuss the AMA\u2019s program\nto meet the medical needs of the\nnation. Before Congressional com\nmittees in Washington, on the\nsame day the resolution was voted,\nCIO and AFL spokesmen called the\nAMA\u2019s program a \u201chorse and\nbuggy\u201d approach. They told LPA,\nthough, that they\u2019ll take part in\nthe conference if invited.\n3\u2014Okayed the formation of a\nnational hospital-cost insurance\nagency, probably an extension of\nBlue Cross, which would enable\nunions to negotiate for Blue Cross\ncoverage in contracts involving\nworkers in more than one state.\nAMA blocked such a proposal last\nwinter.\niiH 4*i-Sent Dr. Morris Fishbein, the\nbld warhorse in the battle against\n\u2018\"progressive health programs, out\nto pasture. He was summarily\nstripped of his multitude of editor\nial and public relations functions,\nand ordered to make no public\nstatements during the time he\nstays on AMA\u2019s payroll to train\nsuccessors. His only comment was\nInsurance\nMiners Quit Work\nIn Effort To\nReduce Coal Stock\nWashington (LPA)\u2014About half\na million coal miners in hard and\nsoft coal fields ftayed away from\nwork this week, in response to a\nUnited Mine Workers directive.\nIn calling for the work stoppage\nUMW President John L. Lewis last\nweek said: \u201cThis period of inaction\nwill emphasize a lack of general\nstability in the industry and the\ndangers which will accrue there\nfrom if current harmful practices\nare not remedied.\u201d\nWith at least 52 days\u2019 supply of\ncoal already above ground, not\nvery strong complaints were forth\ncoming from coal owners against\nthe union\u2019s policy. Only workers\ndirectly tied to the coal industry,\nlike employes of coal-hauling rail\nroads, will be affected by the \u201cbrief\nstabilizing period of inaction\u201d as\nLewis calls the week-long stop\npage.\nDuring the week Lewis will meet\nwith Harry Moses, president of\nthe US Steel subsidiary, the H. C.\nFrick Coke Co., to discuss a new\ncontract for the \u201ccaptive mines.\u201d\nNegotiations between the UMW\nand the Southern Coal Producers\nAss\u2019n have bogged down.\nAs long ago as the UMW\u2019s Octo\nber 1948 convention, the union\nwarned that if the industry itself\ndid not take steps to stabilize pro\nduction and employment in the\nmines the union would take the\nlead. This weeks\u2019 walk-out is evid\nence of the union\u2019s determination\nto keep its members employed.\nThe miners\u2019 vacation period be\ngins June 20, running till July 5.\nEven if the miners return to work\nnext week, as Lewis\u2019 letter indi\ncated they will, very little coal will\nbe dug during the next four weeks.\nAnd in the middle of the vacation\nperiod the coal contracts expire.\nIn keeping with traditional UMW\npolicy the men will not return to\nthe pits after their holiday unless\nnew contracts have been agreed to.\nWhile some people charged that\nthe UMW move would hurt the\nchances of Taft-Hartley repeal,\nPresident Truman refused to get\nexcited. He called Lewis a \u201chead\nline hunter\u201d, but explained to re\nporters that this is no national\nemergency strike, but a \u201crest\u201d de\nsigned to improve the miners\u2019 bar\ngaining position at the end of the\nmonth.\na laughing denial that he plans to\nwrite a book called \u201cInside AMA.\u201d\nFurniture-- Stoves\nBedding- Curtains\nDrapery-Rugs\u2014Carpets\nPaint\u2014Appliances\nDinner Cooking Ware\nSeven Floors Of Quality Furniture And All Furnish\nings To Make A House A Comfortable Home.\nEstabUahed 1880 Ent Liverpool, Ohl.\nConvenient Term.\nCROOK\u2019S\n\u201cTHE BEST PLACE TO BUT AFTER ALL\u201d\nI\nTIJE ATHLETIC TYPE\u2014A\nphotographer just happened to find\nVom Lester with that oar in her\nhand. Warner Bros, publicity de\npartment claims that she speaks\nSpanish too.\nRail Keymen Urged\nTo Back Fair Deal\nAt Tampa Parley\nTampa, Fla. (LPA)\u2014Six hund\nred delegates to the triennial con\nvention here of the Order of Rail\nroad Telegraphers-AFL heard their\npresident, G. D. Leighty make a\nstirring plea for support of the\n\u201cFair Deal\u201d program in Congress.\nThe 600 represent over 50,000 com\nmunications workers on the \u201cIron\nHorse\u201d in the United States and\nCanada.\nReporting to the opening sess\nions of the two-week conclave,\nLeighty called on all members of\nthe Order to lend support in the\nfight for repeal of the Taft-Hart\nley act and state anti-labor laws,\nand also to push demands for en\nactment of such measures as health\ninsurance, a higher minimum wage,\nand a long-range housing program.\nIn addition, he listed goals the\norganization will seek on the rail\nroads, such as longer vacations,\npaid sick leave, and other improv\ned working conditions.\nLeighty reported that the union\u2019s\nmembership and finances are above\nthe wartime peak. Wage gains\nsince the last convention, plus the\n40-hour week at 48-hours\u2019 pay won\nrecently, will bring the average\npay of ORT members on the rail\nroads to $1.63 an hou, Leighty\nsaid.\nKeep Union spirit at its peak.\nCelebrate Union Label Week!\nIT WILL BE A\nbigger dollar\nLATER ON\nThat dollar you thoughtlessly\npull from your billfold to spend\nnow will be a bigger dollar in\nthe future. Its spending power\ncan be almost doubled when the\npressure of inflation eases. Now\n\u2014more than ever before\u2014is the\ntime to save your money. Put it\nwhere it will do tjie greatest\ngood\u2014come in today and start\na savings account with us.\nSAVE now at\nFirst National\nMember FDIC\nEast Liverpool\u2019s Oldest Bank\nPhone 914\nALWAYS A FAVORITE WITH THE POTTERS\nfor happier\nSPENDING later\nVAN BUREN HOTEL\n37-39 S. KENTUCKY AVE. ATLANTIC CITY. N. J.\nExtends best wishes to members of the National Brotherhood of Operative\nPottefs and hopes to share the pleasure of its members to the convention this\nSPECIAL RATES FOR CONVENTION DELEGATES\nWRITE. WIRE OR PHONE FOR RESERVATIONS\nPhone 49576-45230 John Winters. Prop,\nSFi e\nTHE POTTERS HERALD, EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\nPower Trust Found\nAiding Lobby To[\nCurb Cooperatives\nWashington (LPA)\u2014The frown\nTrust wiu, revealed last week to\nhave been one of the main contri\nbutors to the Nat\u2019l Tax Equality\nAssociation, the propaganda and\nlobbying organization which\nbeen seeking legislation to cripj\ncooperatives.\nAt least 16 power compani\ngave money to the NTEA, the Co\noperative League of the USA d'\nclosed. They provided a sizeal\nshare of the $139,978 collected by\nthe NTEA.during the first quarter\nof 1949, according to the associa\ntion\u2019s own reports filed with Con\ngress under the Lobby Regulation\nAct. That\u2019s in addition to a \u201cbal\nance\u201d of $198,848 reported by the\norganization as of January 4.,\nI\nThat the NTEA doesn\u2019t relish\n\u201cpitiless publicity\u201d was made plain\nwhen its representatives appealed\nto Rep. Wright Patman (D, Tex.),\nchairman of the House Committee\non Small Business, to make no fur\nther inquiry into the NTEA\u2019s oper\nations.\nPatman insisted his committee\nwould go on with its probe and that\ninvestigators would be sent to\nNTEA headquarters to determine\nwhat records should be reported to\nthe House Committee.\nThis investigation is a follow\nup on an inquiry conducted by the\nsame committee at the last session\ninto the activities of cooperatives.\nAt that time, the committee was\nunder Republican control. The \u2019\u2019lo\nops\u201d had nothing to hide and pre\nsented full reports, but the NTEA\nis having hysteria over the idea of\nbeing placed under the spotlight.\nIncidentally, the financial report\nfor the first quarter of 1949 was\nthe first to be filed by the NTEA\nunder the Lobby Act. The NTEA\u2019s\nalibi for its failure to file up to\nnow was that its previous charter\ndidn\u2019t include lobbying as an objec\ntive, but that the charter has now\nbeen changed.\nThe Coop League questioned that\nalibi. \u201cThere is belief that the\nNTEA, knowing Patman would get\nthe records, decided to file a re\nport and hope that Patman could\nbe induced to abandon his work,\u201d\nthe League said. \u201cPatman refused.\u201d\nPetrillo Warns\nMusicians They\u2019re\nIn Tight Spot 1\nSan Francisco (LPA) Music\nians are in a tight spot economic\nally, President James C. Petrillo of\nAmerican Federation of Musicians\nAFL told his union\u2019s convention\nhere.\nIn the interests of reviving\nvaudeville, the only chance for 18,\n000 to 21,000 unemployed theatre\nmusicians, Petrillo urged AFM\nlocals to adjust their wage de\nmands to encourage small theatre\noperators.\nLast year\u2019s recording strike, he\nbluntly admitted, was forced to an\nunsatisfactory settlement because\nth\u00bb union\u2019s own members were\nbootlegging records. They needed\nthe money. The union chief predict\ned that a strike for royalties in\nthe motion picture industry now\nwould be a flop because the studios\nhave so much canned music saved\nup \u201cthey wouldn\u2019t give a damn if\nwe never came back to work.\u201d\nPetrillo received enthusiastic ap\nplause from the delegates when he\npromised action as soon as it be\ncomes practical. \u201cEverything re\nsolves itself down to economic\nstrength,\u201d he declared. \u201cThe em\nployer won\u2019t do anything unless\nyou stop him from making money.\nYou\u2019d probably do the same thing\nif you were in his place.\u201d\nI try not to be envious but con\nfess relucti ntly that when a man\ndies and leaves a couple of million\nto somebody I know I feel, well,\nyou *know.\nIf you\u2019re naturally kind you at\ntract a lot of people you don\u2019t like.\n\u2018\u25a0fa'/\u25a0\u25a0/\n\"#7 1\ncli\nplan aid.\nHEALTHY KIDS\u2014The British people may be tiring of austerity,\nbut most Englishmen applaud the Lalor government\u2019s insi ne t:.a\u2019\nchildren\u2019s health is a rrnjor respor\"ibihty of the comntrmi*y. 'P\u25a0 k i i\nare getting\nMany of the power big-wigs as\nserted that the present, admittedly\nmoderate, expansion plans of the\nprivate industry are sufficient.\nOnly the Pacific northwest lacks\nsufficient power, was the general\ntheme.\nMost interesting speaker, how\never, was Charles E. Wilson, pres\nident of the General Electric Co.\nHe assured the utilities men that\nthe decline in industrial production\nnow underway will lessen the pub\nlic demand for expansion of power\nfacilities.\nWilson predicted that downward\ntendency will continue until the\nlast quarter of 1950. gy that time\nproduction will be 15' below the\n1948 average, Wilson said, and then\nit\u2019ll start upward again, reaching\n1948 levels by the end of 1951.\nHowever, the GE head declared,\nthere\u2019ll be nothing like the depres\nsion of the early \u201936s. The absence\nof speculative excess inventories,\ncurrent production and price cuts,\naijd government social security and\nfarm-price support programs rule\nthis out in his opinion.\nWilson opinioned that a little\nrecession will be good for the coun\ntry, and said that the electrical in\ndustry will cut consumers goods\nproduction 20% and industrial pro\nduction 10% by the end of 1949.\nGarment Workers\nBoard Reports\nOrganizing Gains\nUnity House, Pa. (LPA)\u2014Or\nganzing gains in the New York\ndress industry and thruout the\ncountry were reported to last\nweek\u2019s meeting of the executive\nboard of the lnt\u20191 Ladies Garment\nWorkers Union-AFL.\nOver 7000 new members have\nbeen recruited in the New York\norganizing drive, in the course of\nwhich gangsters murdered one\nILGWU organizer recently. No\nprogress in apprehending his kill\ners has yet been reported by NY\npolice.\nPresident David Dubinsky told\nthe board that the union has man\naged to keep up wages in the gar\nment industry, despite declining\nproduction. In some cases, he said,\nthe union has had to forego wage\ndemands because of lower employ\nment and a tightening market.\nAt least 89% of the ILGWU\u2019s\nmore than 400,000 members are\nnow covered by the union\u2019s social\nsecurity contract provisions, Dub\ninsky reported. The funds paid out\nover $18,000,000 last year in health,\nvacation and pension benefits.\nThe board voted to purchase\n$1,000,000 of bonds to finance\nhousing developments in Israel.\nUnion members are expected to\ntake another $2,000,000 worth.\ncentralorange juice, mad' in the IS, thru Mar aH\nTycoons Pledge Battle\nTo BlockPublic Power\nAtlantic City (LPA) Nearly\n3000 of the leading figures in the\n$17,500,000,000 private power in\ndustry met here last week. It was\nthe convention of the Edison Elec\ntric Institute.\nThey renewed their oft repeated\npledges to battle to the death Pre\nsident Truman and other advocates\nof public power development, and\naccepted with good grace a predic\ntion that the recession now under\nway in America will last until\n1951.\nSpeaker after speaker agreed\nwith Elmer L. Lindseth, Cleveland\npower executive, that the utilities\nmen must launch a \u201cgrass roots\ncampaign\u201d to convince the Ameri\ncan people of the ability of \u201cbusi\nness managed power companies\u201d\nto fill the nation\u2019s power needs.\nLindseth who was elected pres\nident of the Institute, said that the\nindustry will \u201cdevelop a sound\npublic understanding by use of all\nchannels of information to em\nployes, neighbors and customers.\u201d\nSeconding his remarks was a\nguest speaker\u2014Chairman Morris\nSayre of the NAM. He said that\ncorporation heads in the manufac\nturing and utilities industries must\ngive their \u201c12,000,000 employes the\neconomic facts of life to offset col\nlectivist propaganda.\u201d\nTwo things disturb me today.\nOne is the Hickenlooper attadk\non Lilienthal the other is the 24\nday Ford strike.\nMaybe I shouldn\u2019t be bothered\nby either one, but it\u2019s the kind of\na day that invites being bothered.\nOf course there are so many\nthings about which to be bothered\nthat one ought to make a list of\nthem and then each morning ask\nhimself, \u201cwhat am I going to be\nbothered about today?\u201d That\nwould put some system into the\nbusiness of being bothered about\npublic affairs.\nBut anyway, those are the two\nthings I\u2019ve picked for today\u2019s both\nerment.\nFirst about Mr. Hickenlooper. It\nseems to me he has touched off a\nstring of half wet firecrackers,\nwhen he promised the booming of\nreally big guns.\nWhat we see is the case with\nwhich a man can be put in the\nstocks before the public. Easy to\nmake charges hard to get them\nwiped out, no matter how puny\nthey are.\nMr. Hickenlooper talked about\n\u201cincredible\u201d mismanagement, but\nall he has shown us thus far is \u201cin\ncredible\u201d exaggeration and bom\nbast.\nThe story of the \u201cmissing\u201d uran\nium is about as flat as a pancake.\nIt is about as exciting, in the light\nof subsequent testimony, as the\nthought of Little Eva scampering\nover the ice cakes.\nIf Mr. Hickenlooper isn\u2019t very\ncareful he will find a new noun has\nbeen added to the language, so\nthat hereafter men may be said to\nhave \u201cpulled a hickenlooper\u201d and\nmaybe also a new verb, \u201cto hicken\nloop\u201d.\nIt\u2019s so easy to hang a mess of\ncharges around a man\u2019s neck, if\nyou are a member of Congress,\nclothed with immunity. And it is\nso easy then to demand and get an\nexpensive \u201cinvestigation\u201d, which\ncan be dragged along, inconclusive\nly, until the only memory left is\nthat charges were made.\nIt may be that Mr. Lilienthal has\nmade mistakes. Probably he has\nmade them.\nBut from my window it looks as\nif Mr. Hickenlooper has shown us,\nup to this hour, that democracy\ncan stand a lot of growing up and\nthat we have members of Congress\nwho should much more carefully\nweigh their words and their\ncharges.\nNow let\u2019s talk about the Ford\nstrike. It is safe, since the strike\nis over.\nThat strike went 24 days and\nended right where it might have\nended the first day, or even before\nit started.\nThe same thing has happened\nrepeatedly, in AF of and well as\nin CIO. It is easy to understand\nthe position of men caught in an\nissue. There is the feeling that in\nconflict one must stand up to\u2018his\nguns.\nBut there is something else and\nthat is STATESMANSHIP and a\ndue regard for the rest of the na\ntion.\nIndustry as big as Ford stands\nstill only at terrific cost to manage\nment, workers, AND THE NA\nTION.\nThe flow of dollar energy out of\nsuch plants ramifies through a\ngreat part of the whole nation\u2019s\neconomy.\nAny conflict within such a plant\nis actually the concern of the na\ntion and both parties to the im\nmediate dispute should so regard\nit. They have a terrific responsi\nbility when they talk about stop\nping the wheels.\nThe day must come when demo\ncratic processes in industry must\nbe so operated as to make things\nEastern Labor Editors\nRap Post Office Dept-\nWashington (LPA) Uncle\nSam\u2019s Postoffice Department won\u2019t\nneed a letter to know that labor\neditors take a dim view of the de\npartment\u2019s present system ef re\nturning wrongly-addressed papers.\nWhat the editors think about the\nst\u2019 jp was told to a Postoffice De\npartment representative face to\nface at the annual meeting here of\nthe Eastern Labor Press Confer\nence.\nRoy C. Frank, associate solicitor\nof tMe department, got a mouthful\nfrom the 50 editors who attended,\nrepresenting papers from all parts\nof the country east of the Missis\nsippi.\nThey made it clear they disliked\nthe department\u2019s practice of hav\ning pink stickers pasted over in\ncorrect addresses on their papers.\nThese slips have got to be steamed\noff to get at the addresses under\nneath, the editors complained.\n..3 Garland Ruark, editor of the\nBaltimore Fede rationalists put it:\n\u201cWe steam and we tear we curse\nand we swear, but it doesn\u2019t do any\ngood.\u201d\nThe editors also protested the\ndepartment\u2019s procedure of letting\nwrongly-addressed papers accumu\nlate for weeks at a time before\nthey\u2019re shipped back.\nBig Business In Badger State Tries\nTo Undermine Food Law Enforcement\nMadison, Wis. (LPA)\u2014The Bad-'\nger state isn\u2019t what it used to be\nin the heyday of the LaFollette\nProgressives. The change\u2014at least\ninsofar as consumers are concern\ned\u2014was spotlighted in an angry\neditorial published by the militant\nCapital Tiroes of this city.\nBig business elements, now in\ncontrol of the legislature, are mov\ning step by step to undermine pure\nfood laws put on the statute books\nin the LaFollette era, the Capital\nTimes pointed out. It denounced\nthe bills passed by the legislature\nwhich would permit food processors\nto adulterate their products.\nThe Capital Times charged too\nthat the state Agriculture Dep\u2019t,\nresponsible for enforcing the pure\nfood standards, has permitted vio\nlations to go on unchallenged. If\nthis trend goes on, it warned,\n\u201cthere won\u2019t be any pure food laws\nleft in Wisconsin.\u201d\nIn an interview with an attorney\nfor the Agriculttire Dep\u2019t, the\nTimes got shocking admissions of\nthe extent to which the pure food\nlaws are becoming a dead letter.\n\u201cThere are a whole mass of pro\nducts which do not comply with\nstate pure food standards,\u201d said\nAnthony Madler, attorney for the\ndepartment. \u201cIf we tried to enforce\nthe pure food laws fully, we would\nempty every grocery shelf in the\nstate.\u201d\nWhy are the wholesale evasions\npermitted? Because the depart\nment hasn\u2019t adequate staff to check\non them, Madler declared. Some of\nthe big chains, he said, would rath\ner be penalized than obey the law.\n\u201cSuppose,\u201d for example, we pro\nsecute a chain .store for selling can\nned peaches with dextrose,\u201d he ad\nded. \u201cEven if we got a conviction,\nthey would just pay the- fine and\ncontinue to sell in violation of the\nlaw. We couldn\u2019t keep the food\nstuffs off the market.\u201d\nAnother Madler alibi was that\nsome of the requirements in the\npure food laws are \u201cout of date\u201d\nand should be changed. The legis\nlature is changing them, but not\nin the direction of protecting the\nconsumers, said the Times.\nrun, not to cause stoppage. Until\nthat day comes there is somewhere\na flaw in .the machinery of demo\ncracy, which, concededly, is only\npartially developed.\nThe subject is one to call for\nheavy thinking by management and\nby union leaders.\nOne highly instructive and most\nhelpful indication of the way dem\nocracy can work in industry was\nfound in the recent union label\ngoods show directed by Dick Orn\nbum, worth its weight in gold.\nThere were the evidences of labor\u2019s\nstatesmanship and industry\u2019s un\nderstanding of today\u2019s require-.\nments. I\nThe public will always be with\nthose who have a regard for public\nwelfare.\n-J I -y\u00a3\nPAGE FIVE\nFrank listened to the \u201cbeefs\u201d,\nall he W\"uld promise is that he\n\u25a0wUiM take th ^m u\u00bb Ute lugher-ups\nin t.-\u2022\u25a0 Post fii 8.\nAt the same session, the editors\nalso adopt'd a resolution opposing\nthe department\u2019s proposed sharp\nx.ujf\nLicruaJe in gec-md mail\nrates. The resolution said the new\nrates would be a severe blow to\noi.\u2019iny .-ma\u2019! pap* rs, nml th- urged\nthat exirintg xutes be retained as\na public rvice.\nDelegates re-elected Editor\nFrank Powers of the Comnu rcial\nTelegri~hers\u2019 Journal as pr---ilrnr\nand LuTaylor, who pJjL. a\ncolumn for the labor press, as\nretary-treasurer.\nVice preside el^jd and their\npapers are:\nL-a\nis IRrmtuai. New\nJersey Labor rald Fr 1 Walker*\nWashington Trades Unionist John\nBookjams, Catering Employe, pub\nlished by Hotel A Restaurant Em\nployes Leon Schachter, Union Re\nporter organ of Eastern locals at\nthe Meat Cutters A Butcher Work\nmen Joseph Springer, Train Dis\npatcher Irwin I :ppe, trainman.\nNews, and Edward Wall, Paper\nMaker. Circulation representation\nat the conference was over 2,066,\n000, the officers said.\nSteel Industry\nStarts Anti-Wage\nRaise Propaganda\nPittsburgh (LPA)\u2014The steel in\ndustry got its anti-wage raise pro\npaganda under way last week.\nIrving S. Olds, chairman of US\nSteel, in a speed) at Salt Lake City,\ntried to convince his audience tli n\nit\u2019s impossible for \u201coutsiders\u201d to\nreally understand steel profits. A\nlegitimate rate of profit can or!-.\nbe determined by those who kno w\n\u201cwhat is wise and advisable in light\nof everything that has a true bear\ning on the subject,\u201d Olds said.\nTo the ordinary ciM~?n\nfacts about steel pruixts luxxx^xxxcd\nclear, however.\nThe 22 big steel companies which\naccount for 84% of the nation\u2019s\ningot ca: ity had net profits of\n$101,7TO,Uwl for the first quarter\nof 1948 and $174,948,720 for the\ncorresponding period this year. US\nSteel itself increased net ear\u2019 i igs\nfrom $27,757,341 to $49,928,670.\nThinly veiled indications of the\nindustry\u2019s determination to fort-u\na fight with the United Steelwork\ners of America mount every week\nin the pages of journals like Iron\nAge, the steel industry\u2019s own trade\npaper, Business Week and the\nJournal of Commerce.\nThe industry is continuing to\nstockpile coal from its \u201ccnp\u2018ivc\nmines\u201d in expectation of a n..x~r\nstrike, while the auto industry\nstockpiles steel, hunching a steel\nworkers strike.\nUS Steel, and leading members\nof the \u201cLittle Steed\u201d fraternity, re\ncently replied to bargaining sum\nmons that while they would discuss\nwages and health insurance they\nwould not deal with the union on\npension proposals this year. They'\nadded that \u201cgeneral business uncer\ntainty and the decreasing cost of\nliving\u201d makes this an inopportune\ntime for the union to press its de\nmands.\nA union spokesman summed up\nthe union\u2019s attitude this way: \u201cI\nthink it is the business of USA to\npress for our demands. I am not\nthreatening. I do not say there\nmust be a strike. I sincerely hope\nnot. But I do say that our people\nare going to get out of this ixxuus\ntry, God willing a more decent\ntreatment than has ever been ac\ncorded them before.\u201d\nTEXAS FACES RENT BOOSTS\nAustin, Tex. (LPA)\u2014Tenants of\nthe state are waiting hopefully to\nsee whether or not the governor\ndecides to veto a bill to decontrol\nall rents in the state\u2014a measure\npassed by the state legislature de\nspite the opposition of veterans\u2019\nand labor organizations.\nRESOLUTIONS OF RESPECT\nWhereas, Almighty God in His infinite wisdom, has seen\nfit to take from our midst our friend and fellow worker,\nBrother Clifford Culler, respected and admired for his fellow\nship and character, and\nWhereas, We the members of Local Union 31, recogn-rr\nthe loss of this Brother, and shall cherish and respect th\nmemory of his pleasant manner and as evidence of sympathy\nand esteem, it is hereby further,\nResolved, That we extend our profound sympathy to his\nfamily, a copy of this resolution be published in our o .r:al\njournal, The Potters Herald, a copy spread upon the i\nof the Local, and a copy sent to the bereaved family, also\nthat our charter be draped in mourning for a period of thirty\ndays.\nEDWARD WOODS\nWILLIS CARTWRIGHT\nROBERT YOUNG\nut-","height":"26211","width":"20991"}}
